However, the substantial wide spectrum of LSPR poses a critical challenge for broad solar absorption in solar thermal systems. Plasmonic NPs offer a solution by serving them as a source to convert solar illumination into localized fields, thereby directing light to specific locations with nanometer precision. To harvest from visible to NIR spectral range, optical absorption traits can be tuned by altering several governing parameters, such as size, morphology, and compositions of NPs. This ensures to accurately match with solar radiation spectrum employing NPs, facilitating an enhanced optothermal conversion in energy harvesting applications [66–68]. Notably, nanoshells (NS), comprising a core (e.g. TiO


                           2

                     ) enveloped by a thin metal layer, exhibit a robust coupling between free electrons inside as well as outside of the shell, resulting in broad LPR spectrum [69,70]. Adjusting the size of nanoshells enables significant tuning of their absorption spectrum to efficiently coincide the solar-based spectrum, thereby improving solar energy harvesting compared to bare particles [66]. However, there are still deficiencies in aligning well with solar radiation spectrum, acquiring for utilization of hybrid NFs (mixtures of varying sizes and shapes). Consequently, the hybrid effect of LPR-based spectrum by suspension of particles into base-fluid presented the idea of NFs. However, the selection of hybrid NFs is huge challenge due to complex interactions with the aqueous medium to match the solar spectral band [71]. However, using AI advanced technology, the hybrid-based NFs can now be screened rapidly, selecting appropriate size or shape of NPs to achieve optimal performance metrics [72].

The optothermal conversion efficiency of working fluids is significantly affected by their thermal performance. Multifaceted factors, including size, morphology, concentration, base-fluid parameters, stabilization methods, and testing procedures, collectively evaluate this property (Fig. 5
                        ). Comprehending the detailed impacts of such parameters is essential to understand the trends in effective thermal conductivity (

                              k
                              eff

                        ) of working fluids. In this section, we highlight the predominant trends in 

