                           ϕ
                        ), base-fluid traits, stability, temperature, and testing procedures, among other factors.

Many studies have demonstrated the important role of particle shape in influencing thermal conductivity across different applications, from phase change materials (PCMs) to solar collectors and NFs (Fig. 14
                        ). Investigations have shown that non-spherical NPs, e.g. CNTs and nanofibers, can yield strong enhancements in heat conductivity when compared to their spherical counterparts within NF formulations, where NPs are dispersed in a base-fluid. Thermal conductivity experiences a remarkable surge solely in NFs featuring CNTs, nanofibers, or nanowires, attributed to their substantial aspect ratios. Notably, three distinct non-spherical NP configurations roughly amplified thermal conductivity at a ratio of 4.5:2.5:1. Particularly, NRs/ellipsoids with diminutive aspect ratios exhibited a more pronounced enhancement in thermal conductivity per concentration. Additionally, agitating non-spherical particles within the base liquid caused an enhancement in convective heat-transfer coefficient [328]. Xie et al. [256] investigated the thermal conductivity of SiC/water NFs while taking particle morphology into account using the hot-wire approach. Both spherical and cylindrical NPs were included in their investigation, which demonstrated that NFs with cylindrical SiC particles had greater thermal conductivity values than those with spherical particles at similar particle loading. Furthermore, it is clear that NFs of various shapes demonstrate different thermal performance (Fig. 15
                        ).

